{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}
The '''Chatsbury/Bungonia bushfires''' of 1965 was a series of [[bushfire]]s that burned from March 5 to March 14, 1965.  The fires destroyed the [[Southern Highlands, New South Wales]] villages of [[Tallong, New South Wales|Tallong]], [[Wingello, New South Wales|Wingello]], and most of the surrounding [[orchard]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=History: 1950-1969: The growth of local brigades|url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/history|website=NSW Rural Fire Service|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>

The fire is thought to be ignited by a spark from a Chatsbury Station [[angle grinder]].  It quickly spread and covered 620,000 acres and destroyed the areas' livestock.  It is thought to be the greatest disaster in the area.<ref name=Gordon>{{cite web|last1=Gordon|first1=Chris|title=Remembering the 1965 Chatsbury-Bungonia Fire|url=http://www.goulburnpost.com.au/story/2919539/remembering-the-1965-chatsbury-bungonia-fire-photos-audio/|website=Goulburn Post|accessdate=September 14, 2015}}</ref>

Three people were killed. 28 homes were destroyed in Tallong, 31 in Wingello.  The fire was eventually stopped (or burnt out) near [[Nowra]] on the South Coast.<ref>{{cite web|title=History: 1950-1969: The growth of local brigades|url=http://www.rfs.nsw.gov.au/about-us/history|website=NSW Rural Fire Service|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>

