{{refimprove|date=January 2014}}
{{Infobox recurring event | name = One Lagos Fiesta | native_name = | logo = | logo_caption = | image = File:Lagos countdown.webm | caption = | genre = [[New Year's Eve]] event | date = December 31 | begins = | ends = | frequency = Yearly | location = Barbeach, Lagos Island, Epe, Ikorodu, Agege, [[Lagos]] | years_active = | first = 2012 | founder_name = [[Governor]] [[Babatunde Fashola]] | last = 2015 | prev = | next = 2016 | website = [http://www.lagoscountdown.com www.lagoscountdown.com] | attendance = | area = | budget = | patron = | organised = Lagos State Signage & Advertisement Agency (LASAA) | people = | member = | footnotes = }} The '''Lagos Countdown,''' now '''One Lagos Fiesta''', is an annual [[New Year's Eve]] event at the [[Bar Beach, Lagos|Bar Beach]] in [[Lagos]].<ref>{{cite web|title=LASAA unveils plan for 2013 Lagos countdown|url=http://dailyindependentnig.com/2013/11/lasaa-unveils-plan-for-2013-lagos-countdown/|publisher=Daily Independent|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dangote, Zenith Bank, NB, Others Throw Weight Behind Lagos Countdown 2013|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/dangote-zenith-bank-nb-others-throw-weight-behind-lagos-countdown-2013/163809/|publisher=This Day Live|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The event lasts for 21–23 days and traditionally begins on the 7th or 8 December and lasts through January 1 of the new year.<ref name=TDL>{{cite web|last1=Akinsanmi|first1=Gboyega|title=Lagos Countdown to 2014 Begins December 7|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/lagos-countdown-to-2014-begins-december-7/164535/|publisher=This Day Live|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The first Lagos Countdown was held in 2012 as an attempt to drive up tourism and make an event similar to New Year's events in [[Times Square Ball|New York]], [[Sydney New Year's Eve|Sydney]], and other major cities,<ref>{{cite web|title=Lagos Festival: UK fireworks experts arrive|url=http://thenationonlineng.net/new/lagos-festival-uk-fireworks-experts-arrive/|publisher=The Nations|accessdate=12 September 2013}}</ref> and in 2013 an estimated 200,000 people celebrated the event during a ten-day period and earned the city about one billion [[Nigerian naira|naira]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Obi|first1=Daniel|title=Lagos economy earns N1bn from 2012 countdown event|url=http://businessdayonline.com/2013/11/lagos-economy-earns-n1bn-from-2012-countdown-event/#.VJZi8sAD8|publisher=Business Day Online|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>
Festivities for the countdown typically include [[fireworks]], [[live music]] concerts, and [[karaoke]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tuface, Omawunmi for Lagos Countdown|url=http://www.punchng.com/feature/midweek-revue/tuface-omawunmi-for-lagos-countdown/|publisher=Punch Nigeria|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=pulse>{{cite web|last1=Banah|first1=Namang|title=2face, Olamide, Wizkid, Iyanya, M.I, Ice Prince, Daddy Showkey, More|url=http://pulse.ng/events/lagos-countdown-2014-2face-olamide-wizkid-iyanya-m-i-ice-prince-daddy-showkey-more-id3317745.html|publisher=Pulse|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> Performers at various countdowns have included [[Tuface Idibia]], [[Olamide]], and [[Funke Akindele]],<ref name=TDL /><ref name=pulse /> and previous countdown sponsors have included Airtel Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airtel backs Lagos Countdown Festival|url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2013/11/airtel-backs-lagos-countdown-festival/|publisher=Vanguard Nigeria|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>
The 2013 Lagos Countdown was met with criticism from some participants as ticket distribution was held differently from the 2012 event, as tickets were not free and required that many participants purchase their own tickets via [[scalpers]] or to acquire tickets via Countdown sponsors.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|last1=OKULAJA|first1=AYO|title=How Lagos Countdown 2013 Was A Let Down|url=http://saharareporters.com/2014/01/11/how-lagos-countdown-2013-was-let-down|publisher=Sahara Reporters|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> When asked about this, the corporate affairs manager of LASAA responded that while tickets were not intended to have been sold, the different distribution tactics were enacted as a form of crowd control and to avoid potential issues due to overcrowded space.<ref name=SR />
Lagos Countdown was renamed One Lagos Fiesta in 2015.
